\newlabel{the-impact-of-z_1100-and-phi-on-coupling}{{4.2}{25}{\texorpdfstring {The impact of \(z_{1100}\) and \(\Phi \) on coupling}{The impact of z\_\{1100\} and \textbackslash Phi on coupling}}{subsection.4.2}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {9}{\ignorespaces Visualization of temperature, viscosity, and velocity near the coupling region at $\sim $ 10 $Ma$ for model cdf with lithospheric thickness of 78 $km$. Velocity arrows are relative to the model boundaries, so the upper mantle wedge has a leftwards velocity equal to the velocity of the upper plate, but is stagnant with respect to itself. (a) High-velocity mantle flow occurs only beneath the lithospheric base (1100$^{\circ }C$), transfering heat towards the coupling region. (b) Log viscosity indicates coupling at the point where the viscosity contrast between the slab and mantle approaches zero. Reference points a-e are used for discussing reaction mechanisms and thermal feedbacks during the transition to slab-mantle mechanical coupling.\relax }}{26}{figure.caption.17}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:arrows}{{9}{26}{Visualization of temperature, viscosity, and velocity near the coupling region at $\sim $ 10 $Ma$ for model cdf with lithospheric thickness of 78 $km$. Velocity arrows are relative to the model boundaries, so the upper mantle wedge has a leftwards velocity equal to the velocity of the upper plate, but is stagnant with respect to itself. (a) High-velocity mantle flow occurs only beneath the lithospheric base (1100$^{\circ }C$), transfering heat towards the coupling region. (b) Log viscosity indicates coupling at the point where the viscosity contrast between the slab and mantle approaches zero. Reference points a-e are used for discussing reaction mechanisms and thermal feedbacks during the transition to slab-mantle mechanical coupling.\relax }{figure.caption.17}{}}
